Currently CDC log supports altering the table, which is expected, however not all alter options should be allowed such as dropping the colums. 

```
cqlsh> CREATE KEYSPACE ks WITH replication = {'class': 'NetworkTopologyStrategy', 'replication_factor': 1} AND tablets = {'enabled': false};

Warnings :
Using Replication Factor replication_factor=1 lower than the minimum_replication_factor_warn_threshold=3 is not recommended.

cqlsh> CREATE TABLE ks.tbl (pk int, ck int, c int, c_vec vector<float, 3>, PRIMARY KEY (pk, ck)) WITH cdc = {'enabled': true};
cqlsh> ALTER TABLE ks.tbl_scylla_cdc_log DROP c;
cqlsh> ALTER TABLE ks.tbl_scylla_cdc_log DROP "cdc$deleted_c";
cqlsh> INSERT INTO ks.tbl (pk, ck, c, c_vec) VALUES (1, 2, 3, [1, 2, 3]);
NoHostAvailable: ('Unable to complete the operation against any hosts', {<Host: 127.0.0.1:9042 datacenter1>: ConnectionShutdown('Connection to 127.0.0.1:19042 was closed')})`
```
The INSERT query causes a segmentation fault and crashes the database. As I understand, this should not be allowed/should not happen.

