> Memory use: Even if we avoid buffering in .NET or JS, the underlying browser may still
end up consuming memory when the Blob is accessed, especially for very large files.

Blobs are immutable in JS, so if you have a stream you end up having to buffer all the data in memory.

Here is a sample snippet

```js
async function readableStreamToBlob(readableStream, mimeType = "application/octet-stream") {
    const reader = readableStream.getReader();
    const chunks = [];

    while (true) {
        const { done, value } = await reader.read();
        if (done) break;
        chunks.push(value); // Buffering chunks in memory
    }

    return new Blob(chunks, { type: mimeType });
}

// Example usage:
fetch('https://example.com/file') // Fetch returns a Response object with a ReadableStream
    .then(response => readableStreamToBlob(response.body, "application/pdf"))
    .then(blob => console.log(blob));
```

